    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for that. that makes sense. so i was reading that the reaction depends on the pH level too, right? how does that work with the browning process? like, does a more alkaline environment speed things up or what?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, pH is a critical factor, and a more alkaline (basic) environment will definitely speed up the Maillard reaction. The reaction involves the formation of an imine intermediate, which is much more stable in a high-pH environment, allowing the browning and flavor development to occur at lower temperatures. Conversely, a very acidic environment can inhibit the reaction, which is why some foods might brown poorly if the pH is too low.\n\nFor your exam, remember that while the temperature is the primary driver, the pH acts as a catalyst; think of it like a helpful guide that helps the molecules find each other faster in a basic setting. You might also notice this in practice when you add baking soda to mashed potatoes or cornbread batter, which promotes a richer, darker color and a more complex flavor profile. Just be careful not to over-alkalinize, as it can alter the overall taste balance of your dish.",
